{{Infobox book | image = File:Free Will, first edition.jpg | image_size = 200px | author = [[Sam Harris]] | name = Free Will | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[Free will]] | published = 2012 | media_type = Print | isbn = 978-1451683400 | pages = | dewey = | congress = | oclc = | preceded_by = [[Lying (book)|Lying]] | followed_by = [[Waking Up: A Guide to Spirituality Without Religion]] }} '''''Free Will''''' is a 2012 book by American [[neuroscience|neuroscientist]] and author [[Sam Harris]]. Harris argues that the truth about the human [[mind]] (that [[free will]] is an [[illusion]]) does not undermine [[morality]] or diminish the importance of [[political freedom|political]] and [[Liberty|social]] freedom, and can as well as should change the way we think about some of the most important questions in life.<ref>{{Cite news|title = ‘Free Will,’ by Sam Harris|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/15/books/review/free-will-by-sam-harris.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2012-07-13|access-date = 2015-10-31|issn = 0362-4331|first = Daniel|last = Menaker}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Book Review: Sam Harris’ Free Will|url = http://americanhumanist.org/HNN/details/2012-03-book-review-sam-harris-free-will|website = American Humanist Association|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Will This Post Make Sam Harris Change His Mind About Free Will?|url = http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/cross-check/will-this-post-make-sam-harris-change-his-mind-about-free-will/|website = blogs.scientificamerican.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = How free is the will? Sam Harris misses his mark|url = http://www.abc.net.au/religion/articles/2012/04/26/3489758.htm|website = www.abc.net.au|accessdate = 2015-10-31|language = en}}</ref>
==Overview== Harris says the idea of free will "cannot be mapped on to any conceivable reality" and is incoherent.<ref>Pardi, Paul (May 15, 2012). [http://www.philosophynews.com/post/2012/05/15/An-Analysis-of-Sam-Harris-Free-Will.aspx "An Analysis of Sam Harris' Free Will"]. Philosophy News.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Harris|first1=Sam|title=Free Will and "Free Will"|url=https://www.samharris.org/blog/item/free-will-and-free-will|publisher=SamHarris.Org|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> According to Harris, science "reveals you to be a biochemical puppet."<ref>Nahmias, Eddy (August 13, 2012). [https://www.bigquestionsonline.com/content/does-contemporary-neuroscience-support-or-challenge-reality-free-will "Does Contemporary Neuroscience Support or Challenge the Reality of Free Will?"] Big Questions Online.</ref> People's thoughts and intentions, Harris says, "emerge from background causes of which we are unaware and over which we exert no conscious control." Every choice we make is made as a result of preceding causes. These choices we make are determined by those causes, and are therefore not really choices at all. Harris also draws a distinction between conscious and unconscious reactions to the world. Even without free will, consciousness has an important role to play in the choices we make. Harris argues that this realization about the human mind does not undermine morality or diminish the importance of social and political freedom, but it can and should change the way we think about some of the most important questions in life.
==Critique== The book has undergone some critique.<ref>https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/cross-check/will-this-post-make-sam-harris-change-his-mind-about-free-will/</ref><ref>Pardi, Paul (May 15, 2012). [http://www.philosophynews.com/post/2012/05/15/An-Analysis-of-Sam-Harris-Free-Will.aspx "An Analysis of Sam Harris' Free Will"]. Philosophy News.</ref><ref>https://aphilosopherstake.com/2012/07/29/free-will-why-sam-harris-needs-to-read-more-philosophy/</ref><ref>http://www.abc.net.au/religion/articles/2012/04/26/3489758.htm</ref><ref>https://cct.biola.edu/sam-harris-free-will-book-review/</ref>
The author uses the [[Benjamin_Libet#Implications_of_Libet's_experiments|Libet argument]], which has been challenged by Adrian G. Guggisberg and Annaïs Mottaz.<ref>{{cite journal | pmc = 3746176 | pmid=23966921 | doi=10.3389/fnhum.2013.00385 | volume=7 | title=Timing and awareness of movement decisions: does consciousness really come too late? | year=2013 | journal=Front Hum Neurosci | pages=385 | last1 = Guggisberg | first1 = AG | last2 = Mottaz | first2 = A}}</ref> A study by Aaron Schurger and colleagues published in PNAS<ref>http://www.pnas.org/content/109/42/E2904/1</ref> challenged assumptions about the causal nature of the readiness potential itself (and the "pre-movement buildup" of neural activity in general), thus denying the conclusions drawn from studies such as Libet's<ref name="LGW">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/brain/106.3.623 |title=Time of Conscious Intention to Act in Relation to Onset of Cerebral Activity (Readiness-Potential) |year=1983 |last1=Libet |first1=Benjamin |last2=Gleason |first2=Curtis A. |last3=Wright |first3=Elwood W. |last4=Pearl |first4=Dennis K. |journal=Brain |volume=106 |issue=3 |pages=623–42 |pmid=6640273}}</ref> and Fried's.<ref name=Fried>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2010.11.045 |title=Internally Generated Preactivation of Single Neurons in Human Medial Frontal Cortex Predicts Volition |year=2011 |last1=Fried |first1=Itzhak |last2=Mukamel |first2=Roy |last3=Kreiman |first3=Gabriel |journal=Neuron |volume=69 |issue=3 |pages=548–62 |pmid=21315264 |pmc=3052770}}</ref>
